<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911203-0068</DOCNO><DOCID>911203-0068.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Boeing Co.:   Company to Offer 767 Jet   As Base for Awacs Plane</HL><DATE>12/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   BA</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><RE>EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)ITALY (ITA)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)SOUTH KOREA (SK)UNITED STATES (US)WASHINGTON (WA)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Boeing Co. said it plans to offer its 767 jetliner as thenew aircraft platform for the Airborne Warning and ControlSystem, or Awacs, military plane.   The 767 will replace the 707, which is no longer inproduction.</LP><TEXT>   The Seattle company said it is conducting in-depth studies&quot;to define the 767 modifications required to perform theAwacs mission,&quot; after which it will determine price andavailability of the new platform.   A spokesman said a number of countries have expressed aninterest in buying Awacs, including Japan, Italy and SouthKorea. The U.S., Saudi Arabia, France and the United Kingdomcurrently operate Awacs fleets.</TEXT></DOC>